  <chapter number="6" style="c" sid="2CO 6" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="2CO 6:1" />Being those who work together <char style="it">to minister to others</char><char style="sup">[a]</char>,
        we do plead with you to not take in God’s grace and have nothing to show for it. <verse eid="2CO 6:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="2CO 6:2" />In fact, <char style="it">the Old Testament </char>says,
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:2"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:2">I heard you just in time</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:2">And I helped you</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:2">That time you needed to be rescued<char style="sup">[b]</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:2"></para>
    <para style="m" vid="2CO 6:2">Hey! “Just in time” is now—Hey! “The time you needed to be rescued” is now.<verse eid="2CO 6:2"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="2CO 6:3" />Don’t give anyone any reason to be seriously offended<char style="sup">[c]</char> <char style="it">by
        something you did wrong</char>, so that the ministry <char style="it">of God’s grace</char> won’t be
        criticized— <verse eid="2CO 6:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="2CO 6:4" />Uh-uh—leaving others with an impression that’s expected of<char style="it"> </char>God’s ministers, <char
        style="it">and doing this </char>with a good deal of perseverance, <char style="it">doing this </char>in<char
        style="it"> </char>times of distress, in times of privation, while in anguish, <verse eid="2CO 6:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="2CO 6:5" />while being whipped or beaten, while in prison, during riots, while doing hard, grueling work, in sleepless
        nights, while going hungry; <verse eid="2CO 6:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="2CO 6:6" /><char style="it">doing this </char>with purity, with understanding, with patience, with kindness; <char
        style="it">do this </char>in the Holy Spirit, in sincere love, <verse eid="2CO 6:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="2CO 6:7" />with a message of truth<char style="sup">[d]</char>, in <char style="it">the </char>power of God, by
        being armed with the armor and weapons of righteousness that the left and right hands are accustomed
        to handle<char style="sup">[e]</char>; <verse eid="2CO 6:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="2CO 6:8" />through glory and disgrace, through a bad reputation and a good reputation; as though we’re deceived
        and as though we know the truth, <verse eid="2CO 6:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="2CO 6:9" />as though we’re not known or understood and as though we’re known and understood, as though we’re dying
        but—hey—we’re <char style="it">still </char>alive; as though we’re being reprimanded but not sentenced
        to death, <verse eid="2CO 6:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="2CO 6:10" />as though we’re in pain but ever rejoicing, as though we’re poor but becoming quite wealthy, as though
        we own nothing but own everything.<verse eid="2CO 6:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="2CO 6:11" />We haven’t stopped engaging you in dialogue<char style="sup">[f]</char>, Corinthians; our heart is fixed<char
        style="it"> </char>wide open <char style="it">to you</char>. <verse eid="2CO 6:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="2CO 6:12" />Don’t be closed off to us—but <char style="it">with</char> <char style="it">the sort of</char> “closed
        off” <char style="it">which keeps us</char> in your tender affections. <verse eid="2CO 6:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="2CO 6:13" />When it’s your turn to reciprocate (I’m talking to you like I would to a child), open yourselves up <char
        style="it">to us</char>.<verse eid="2CO 6:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="2CO 6:14" />Don’t get unevenly yoked (i.e., like an ox and a donkey yoked together on the same plow harness) with
        unbelievers. What partnership is there between righteousness and lawlessness (i.e., the refusal to be
        restrained by the rules of God or of man)? What do light and darkness have in common? <verse eid="2CO 6:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="2CO 6:15" />What harmony is there between Christ and the Devil<char style="sup">[g]</char>? How does a believer partake
        in joint ventures with an unbeliever? <verse eid="2CO 6:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="2CO 6:16" />How does God’s temple approve of or validate <char style="it">an</char> idol’s <char style="it">temple</char>?
        You are a temple of the Living God, in fact, just as God said,</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:16"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:16">“I will dwell and move among them,</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:16">And I will be their God,</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:16">And they will be my folk-people.<verse eid="2CO 6:16"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="2CO 6:17" />In light of this come out from their midst
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:17">And be separate,” Says the Lord,</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:17">“And don’t touch things which</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:17">Are vile, disgusting, and forbidden to touch<char style="sup">[h]</char>,</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:17">And I will receive you and take you in,<verse eid="2CO 6:17"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="2CO 6:18" />And I will be a Father to you,
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:18">And you will be sons and daughters to Me,”</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="2CO 6:18">Says the Lord Almighty.<verse eid="2CO 6:18"/>
    </para>
