  <chapter number="11" style="c" sid="2CO 11" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="2CO 11:1" />If you would bear with me a bit while I act stupid—scratch that: you are<char style="it"> </char>bearing
        with me. <verse eid="2CO 11:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="2CO 11:2" />You see, I dote over you zealously<char style="sup">[a]</char> with a zealous doting that’s of God, for
        I’ve betrothed you to <char style="it">only </char>one man<char style="sup">[b]</char> <char style="it">in
        order </char>to present <char style="it">to this one man </char>a chaste virgin in Christ. <verse eid="2CO 11:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="2CO 11:3" />I fear that somehow that’s not the case—as the serpent deceived Eve with his cunning trickery, he would
        somehow seduce your minds <char style="it">and draw you </char>away from the simplicity<char style="sup">[c]</char>
        (i.e., straightforward, without conniving, ulterior motives, hidden agendas, or religious quid-pro-quo)
        and the purity which has Christ as its goal.<verse eid="2CO 11:3" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="2CO 11:4" />For indeed, if a passerby stops over and preaches <char style="it">that </char>another <char style="it">person
        is the real </char>Jesus, a person whom we didn’t preach <char style="it">as being the real Jesus</char>,
        or you receive (i.e., take to heart and wholeheartedly embrace) a different spirit which you didn’t receive
        <char style="it">before</char>, or you wholeheartedly embrace<char style="it"> </char>a different good-news-<char
        style="it">type</char> message that you didn’t receive<char style="sup">[d]</char>, you tolerate it with
        no qualms. <verse eid="2CO 11:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="2CO 11:5" />You see, the way I figure, we’re not inferior to these <char style="it">so-called</char> super-apostles
        in any category. <verse eid="2CO 11:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="2CO 11:6" />But even if I’m an amateur when it comes to speaking ability and rhetoric<char style="sup">[e]</char>,
        put that aside—<char style="it">I’m not an amateur</char> when it comes to knowledge and understanding—no—I’ve
        made that apparent to you in every possible way<char style="sup">[f]</char>.<verse eid="2CO 11:6" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="2CO 11:7" />Is it that I committed a sin in humbling and debasing myself so that you would be made to stand on two
        legs<char style="sup">[g]</char>, since I evangelized the good news of the Gospel to you sacrificially
        on my part and delivered it to you free of charge? <verse eid="2CO 11:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="2CO 11:8" />Scratch that—I robbed <char style="it">other </char>churches by drawing a wage <char style="it">from
        them </char>and applying it to your ministry. <verse eid="2CO 11:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="2CO 11:9" />Not only that, when I was staying with you and was in need, I wasn’t a burden to anyone: the comrades<char
        style="sup">[h]</char> who came from Macedonia provided what I needed. My living expenses weren’t a burden
        in any way to you, nor will they be. <verse eid="2CO 11:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="2CO 11:10" />Christ in me unequivocally indicates that this is true<char style="sup">[i]</char>: I won’t be denied
        the opportunity to speak with pride <char style="it">about what we will accomplish in the Lord </char>in
        the region of Achaia<char style="sup">[j]</char>. <verse eid="2CO 11:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="2CO 11:11" />Why would <char style="it">I be denied</char>? Because I don’t love you? God knows for a fact <char style="it">that
        I do</char>.<verse eid="2CO 11:11" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="2CO 11:12" />What I’m doing I’ll continue to do in order to nix the occasion <char style="it">for fault-finding </char>by
        those who are wanting <char style="it">to find such </char>an occasion, so that in <char style="it">the
        specific area </char>that they’re boasting of, everyone will come to the conclusion<char style="sup">[k]</char>
        that they’re also like us. <verse eid="2CO 11:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="2CO 11:13" />In fact, false apostles such as they, workers of deceit, are disguising themselves as apostles of Christ—<verse eid="2CO 11:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="2CO 11:14" />And it’s not surprising: Satan himself disguises himself as an angel of light. <verse eid="2CO 11:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="2CO 11:15" />So there’s not a huge <char style="it">difference</char> if his servants <char style="it">the false apostles</char>
        also disguise themselves as servants of righteousness. The way it ends for <char style="it">these false
        apostles </char>will be in step with their deeds.<char style="sup">[l]</char><verse eid="2CO 11:15" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="2CO 11:16" />Moving on to another topic.<char style="sup">[m]</char> Nobody should take me for a fool, but should
        it be otherwise, accept me even as a fool, so that even <char style="it">as a fool </char>I have some
        little thing <char style="it">or two</char> to say about my tremendous <char style="it">accomplishments</char>.<verse eid="2CO 11:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="2CO 11:17" />What I’m about to say isn’t in line with how the Lord speaks, but are words you’d expect to come out
        of one in <char style="it">the throes of </char>folly—the essence of the boasting <char style="it">you’re
        about to hear</char>.<verse eid="2CO 11:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="2CO 11:18" />Since many are talking up great things they’ve done according to flesh (i.e., from their own ability
        apart from God; taking credit for it personally and not giving God the credit), I’ll talk up my tremendous
        accomplishments too. <verse eid="2CO 11:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="2CO 11:19" />The fact of the matter is, you’re more than happy to tolerate what the fools spout off,<char style="it">
        </char>treating them like they’re<char style="it"> </char>sensible and wise<char style="sup">[A]</char>.<verse eid="2CO 11:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="2CO 11:20" />You put up with someone if he subjugates and oppresses you, if he cheats you out of house and home, if
        he sets you up to take advantage of you, if he lifts <char style="it">himself </char>up <char style="it">in
        arrogance</char>, if he slaps you upside the head<char style="sup">[B]</char>. <verse eid="2CO 11:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="2CO 11:21" />I’m ashamed to say it, <char style="it">but it’s </char>as though <char style="it">you disdain us</char>
        because we’ve become weak in what someone <char style="it">else</char> might dare <char style="it">speak
        proudly about</char>.</para>
    <para style="p" vid="2CO 11:21">I’m talking foolishly, but I’ll dare speak <char style="it">anyways</char>. <verse eid="2CO 11:21"/>
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="2CO 11:22" />Are they native-Hebrew speakers and live by the ancient Jewish culture?—So do I. Are they Israelites?—So
        am I. Are they father-to-son direct descendants and heirs of<char style="sup">[n]</char> Abraham?—So
        am I. <verse eid="2CO 11:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="2CO 11:23" />Are they Christ’s servants (I’m talking like a mad man)?—I’ll up them one: as far as hard labor goes,
        I’ve done more. I’ve spent more time in prison. I’ve received more beatings. I’ve had more near-death
        experiences: <verse eid="2CO 11:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="2CO 11:24" />I’ve received the thirty-nine lash <char style="it">punishment </char>by the Jews five times; <verse eid="2CO 11:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="2CO 11:25" />I’ve been beaten with staffs three times; I was stoned <char style="it">to death </char>once; I was shipwrecked
        three times; I spent twenty-four straight hours floundering out in the ocean<char style="sup">[o]</char>.<verse eid="2CO 11:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="2CO 11:26" />I’ve been on the road many a time <char style="it">walking great distances</char>; I’ve been in danger
        while travelling by river; in danger from robbers; in danger by my fellow countrymen; in danger by those
        in faraway countries; in danger in the city; in danger in the countryside; in danger on the high seas;
        in danger from phony comrades; <verse eid="2CO 11:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="2CO 11:27" />I worked hard, long hours and did heavy manual labor; had many a sleepless night; went long stretches
        with nothing to eat or nothing to drink; fasted many times; was cold because I had nothing to wear<char
        style="sup">[p]</char>— <verse eid="2CO 11:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="2CO 11:28" />Besides those external <char style="it">pressures</char>, <char style="it">there is </char>the <char
        style="it">pressure on the inside of me due to </char>the day-to-day responsibility for all the churches,
        worrying over them. <verse eid="2CO 11:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="2CO 11:29" />Who’s weak (i.e., sickly, frail, or simply unable to muster the strength to face life’s challenges),
        and I’m not weak <char style="it">along with them</char>? Who stumbles<char style="sup">[q]</char> (i.e.
        falls away from the walk of faith; falls into sin; is overcome by temptation; stops following God), and
        I’m not raving <char style="it">over it</char>?<verse eid="2CO 11:29" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="2CO 11:30" />If there has to be proud talk <char style="it">about tremendous things which have taken place</char>,
        I’ll speak proudly about things that have to do with my weakness (i.e., circumstances in which I lacked
        the power in my own self to overcome the difficulties I faced). <verse eid="2CO 11:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="2CO 11:31" />The God and Father of our Lord Jesus—He Who’s blessed forevermore—knows for a fact that I’m not lying—<verse eid="2CO 11:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="2CO 11:32" />In Damascus the governor under King Aretas kept the <char style="it">entire </char>city of Damascus on
        alert searching for me in order to arrest me, <verse eid="2CO 11:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="2CO 11:33" />and I was <char style="it">put </char>through<char style="it"> </char>a window in the <char style="it">city
        </char>wall and lowered to the ground in a basket and slipped out of his hands.<verse eid="2CO 11:33" />
    </para>
